<worksheet label="ws-act-1-8-3">
  <activity xml:id="act-1-8-3">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Consider <m>f(x) = 0.1 x^2 - 1.1x + 3.4</m> and <m>g(x) = -0.5x^2 + 2.5x - 2</m>.  
      </p>
      <p/>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="5cm" xml:id="act-1-8-3-task-0">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>f(3)</m>, <m>f'(3)</m>, <m>g(3)</m>, and <m>g'(3)</m>.  What do you observe?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Use the given formulas for <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p><m>f(3) = 1</m>, <m>f'(3) = -0.5</m>, <m>g(3) = 1</m>, and <m>g'(3) = -0.5</m>; this means <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> will have the same tangent line approximation at <m>x = 3</m>.  
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We find that <m>f(3) = 1</m>, <m>f'(3) = -0.5</m>, <m>g(3) = 1</m>, and <m>g'(3) = -0.5</m>, and thus we observe that <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> share the same value and the same slope at <m>x = 3</m>.  This means they will have the same tangent line approximation at <m>x = 3</m>.  
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="5cm" xml:id="act-1-8-3-task-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine <m>L(x)</m>, the local linear approximation to <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x = 3</m>.  Explain why this function is also the local linear approximation to <m>g(x)</m> at <m>x = 3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Remember that for a given value <m>x = a</m>, the local linearization to <m>y = f(x)</m> is <m>L(x) = f(a) + f'(a)(x-a)</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p><m>L(x) = 1 - 0.5(x-3)</m> is the tangent line approximation for both <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> at <m>x = 3</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We know that for a given value <m>x = a</m>, the local linearization to <m>y = f(x)</m> is <m>L(x) = f(a) + f'(a)(x-a)</m>.  Thus, using <m>a = 3</m> and the given function <m>f</m>, we have <m>L(x) = f(3) + f'(3)(x-3) = 1 - 0.5(x-3)</m>.  This is the same tangent line approximation as that of the function <m>g</m> at <m>x = 3</m> since <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> share the same value and the same slope at <m>x = 3</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
