      <task workspace="1cm" xml:id="act-1-8-3-task-3">
        <statement>
          <p>
            On the axes provided in <xref ref="Fig-act-1-8-3-axes">Figure</xref>, plot <m>f(x)</m>, <m>g(x)</m>, and <m>L(x)</m> near <m>x = 3</m>.  In addition, compute <m>f''(3)</m>, <m>g''(3)</m>, and <m>L''(3)</m>.  How do the second derivative values and the graph explain why <m>L(x)</m> is a better approximation for one of the functions than it is for the other?
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="Fig-act-1-8-3-axes">
            <caption>Axes for plotting <m>f(x)</m>, <m>g(x)</m>, and <m>L(x)</m> near <m>x = 3</m>.</caption>
            <image width="50%">
              <prefigure label="F-act-1-8-3-axe" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <coordinates bbox="(-1,-3,6,4)">
