        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            How do the concavities of <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> differ near <m>x = 3</m>?
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <image width="60%">
            <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="F-act-1-8-3-ans">
              <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                <definition>f(x) = 0.1*x**2 - 1.1*x + 3.4</definition>
                <definition>g(x) = -0.5*x**2 + 2.5*x - 2</definition>
                <definition>L(x) = 1 - 0.5*(x - 3)</definition>
                <definition>a = 3</definition>
                <coordinates bbox="(-1,-3,6,4)"><grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                  <graph function="f"/><graph function="g" stroke="darkmagenta"/>
                  <graph function="L" stroke="red"/>
                  <point p="(a,f(a))" alignment="nw" clear-background="yes">
                    <!-- <m>(-4,f(-4))</m> --></point>
                    <label anchor="(1,f(1))" alignment="ne"><m>f(x) </m></label>
                    <label anchor="(1.7,L(1.7))" alignment="sw"><m>L(x) </m></label>
                    <label anchor="(0.4,g(0.4))" alignment="se"><m>g(x) </m></label>
                    <!-- <point p="(b,f(b))" alignment="se" clear-background="yes"><m>(2,f(2))</m></point> -->
                  </coordinates>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
            <p>
              Since <m>f''(3) = 0.2</m> ande <m>g''(3)=-1</m>, <m>g</m> has <q>more</q> concavity at <m>x = 3</m> than <m>f</m>, so <m>L(x)</m> is a closer approximation of the value of <m>f(x)</m> than of the value of <m>g(x)</m> near <m>x = 3</m>.
            </p>
          </answer>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Below we  plot <m>f(x)</m>, <m>g(x)</m>, and <m>L(x)</m> near <m>x = 3</m>.  
            </p>
            <image width="60%"><prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="F-act-1-8-3-soln">
              <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                <definition>f(x) = 0.1*x**2 - 1.1*x + 3.4</definition>
                <definition>g(x) = -0.5*x**2 + 2.5*x - 2</definition>
                <definition>L(x) = 1 - 0.5*(x - 3)</definition>
                <definition>a = 3</definition>
                <coordinates bbox="(-1,-3,6,4)">
                  <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                  <graph function="f"/><graph function="g" stroke="darkmagenta"/>
                  <graph function="L" stroke="red"/>
                  <point p="(a,f(a))" alignment="nw" clear-background="yes"><!-- <m>(-4,f(-4))</m> --></point>
                  <label anchor="(1,f(1))" alignment="ne"><m>f(x) </m></label>
                  <label anchor="(1.7,L(1.7))" alignment="sw"><m>L(x) </m></label>
                  <label anchor="(0.4,g(0.4))" alignment="se"><m>g(x) </m></label>
                  <!-- <point p="(b,f(b))" alignment="se" clear-background="yes"><m>(2,f(2))</m></point> -->
                </coordinates></diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
            <p>
              In the figure, we see how <m>g(x)</m> bends away from <m>L(x)</m> faster than <m>f(x)</m> does.  This is because <m>f''(3) = 0.2</m>, while <m>g''(3)=-1</m>, so <m>g</m> has <q>more</q> concavity at <m>x = 3</m> than <m>f</m>.  As a result, <m>L(x)</m> is a closer approximation of the value of <m>f(x)</m> than of the value of <m>g(x)</m> near <m>x = 3</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
